  accentWord="HVAC"
  subhead="It is 10:30am on a Thursday in July. You are in the plant room of a four-storey office building in Oxford Science Park — pulling a standing vacuum on a newly installed Fujitsu Airstage VRF system. The vacuum pump has been running for forty-five minutes, the micron gauge reads 480 and is dropping steadily toward the target of 500 microns, and you must hold this vacuum undisturbed for a further thirty minutes to confirm system integrity before charging with R32. Any interruption — a door opening, vibration from the pump being knocked, or the hoses being disturbed — risks a false reading that invalidates the test and adds another hour to the procedure. Four calls come in between 10am and noon. Your phone is on the plant room shelf, your eyes on the micron gauge. Without Missed Call Text Back, one voicemail — 'need air conditioning for our office' — three hang-ups. With it, all four receive texts within seconds. The first replies at 10:45am: 'Hi — we manage a medical centre in Summertown with eight consulting rooms, a waiting area, and a pharmacy dispensary. Current cooling is three ancient Daikin wall splits that struggle in summer and two have started leaking condensate. Want to replace with ceiling cassettes — individual temperature control for each consulting room is essential as some doctors run cold while others overheat. Also need dedicated cooling for the server/comms room. The pharmacy dispensary needs humidity control for medication storage. Building has suspended ceilings throughout. Can you survey and design? We are available most mornings.' At 12:15pm the vacuum holds. Four leads on your dashboard — including the eight-room medical centre with pharmacy humidity control."
  scenario="It is 2pm on a freezing January Wednesday. You have been in the ceiling void of a new-build office in Bicester since 7am — installing 156 metres of Armaflex-insulated copper refrigerant pipework for a Toshiba SMMS-e VRF system, brazing joints with nitrogen purge, fitting fire collars at every floor penetration, and connecting sixteen ceiling cassettes to the branch controllers. Six missed calls between 7am and 2pm. Without Missed Call Text Back, you emerge to six unknowns and one voicemail. With Missed Call Text Back, all six received texts. Reply one: 'homeowner Charlbury — ASHP stopped heating, outdoor unit iced, Samsung monobloc 3 years old, no heating, baby, need urgent.' Reply two: 'architect Woodstock — barn conversion needs MVHR plus ASHP, 4-bed, listed building, conservation area, underfloor heating throughout.' Reply three: 'facilities manager Abingdon — chiller compressor failed, air-cooled Carrier 300kW, server hall at 28°C and rising, need emergency attendance.' Reply four: 'developer Didcot — twenty houses need Mitsubishi Ecodan ASHP plus Zehnder MVHR, MCS certified, BUS grant, Part L 2025 compliance.' Reply five: 'restaurant owner Wallingford — kitchen extract fan seized, extract hood not pulling, smoke filling the kitchen.' Reply six: 'homeowner Botley — want multi-split AC for master bedroom and home office, Daikin or Mitsubishi, south-facing house.' Six leads. Wednesday evening you triage — the iced Samsung and the Carrier chiller first, the barn and the twenty houses second."
